{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d287d4b6-fd7f-4892-9f32-34910125f6f1","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports (`.ips` files) when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **User crashes:** `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **System crashes:** `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for `.ips` files matching your process name and timestamp, e.g.:\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For core dumps** (if you need a full memory dump), enable them with:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nThen run your app again — the core file will appear in `/cores/`.\n\n> **Tip:** If you have an `.ips` crash log with native frames from `libcoreclr.so` or the NativeAOT runtime, I can help symbolicate it using the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d737f33-f6d2-4bd7-92f3-93e02933644e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a knowledge question - I don't need to search a codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports (.ips files) in specific locations. For NativeAOT apps (which don't have the CoreCLR createdump tool), you rely on macOS's built-in crash reporting.","outputTokens":380,"requestId":"1B83:31BA5F:D83061:F79301:6A028690"},"id":"a4efd8ae-1812-4a88-9d3f-fee5ca86925e","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:47:07.019Z","parentId":"4ff3f985-d15a-43d8-853b-738c47637df6"}
